---
/**
 * /case-studies/bt-london — BT–Toshiba London commercial QKD metro
 * network. Launched April 2022, initial three-year operating term.
 */
import Infographic from "../../layouts/Infographic.astro";
import Center from "../../components/Center.astro";
import Stack from "../../components/Stack.astro";
import SiteNav from "../../components/SiteNav.astro";
import SourceNote from "../../components/SourceNote.astro";
import { url } from "../../lib/url";

const sections = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Overview" },
  { id: "what",     label: "What it is" },
  { id: "verified", label: "Verified claims" },
  { id: "caveats",  label: "Things to note" },
  { id: "related",  label: "Related entries" },
];
---

<Infographic
  title="BT–Toshiba London commercial QKD metro"
  description="The first commercial QKD-secured metro network sold as a service in the UK. Launched 26 April 2022 with BT operating the network and Toshiba supplying the QKD hardware; EY was the launch customer, connecting its Canary Wharf and London Bridge offices."
  references={[
    "bt-toshiba-press-2022",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="case-studies" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>BT–Toshiba London commercial QKD metro</h1>
        <p>
          A QKD-secured metro network sold as a managed service. BT operates
          the fibre and the service wrapper; Toshiba supplies the QKD
          hardware. The first customer, EY, used the network to link its
          Canary Wharf office to its London Bridge office, with launch on
          26 April 2022 and an initial three-year operating term.
        </p>
        <dl class="hero-meta">
          <div><dt>Operator</dt><dd>BT (managed service) · Toshiba (QKD devices) · EY (launch customer)</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Location</dt><dd>London, UK (City / Canary Wharf metro fibre)</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Year</dt><dd>Launched 26 April 2022; initial three-year term</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Technology</dt><dd>Prepare-and-measure QKD over standard fibre-optic links; Toshiba QKD systems developed at the Cambridge labs</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Scale</dt><dd>London metro</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Status</dt><dd>Operational commercial trial</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Commercial model</dt><dd>Paid managed service; EY connected two offices and pays for the QKD-secured channel</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </header>

      <section id="what" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What it is</h2>
        <p>
          BT and Toshiba launched the network at BT Tower on 26 April 2022,
          with EY as the first commercial customer. The infrastructure is a
          metro QKD overlay on standard fibre, marketed as the first
          commercial trial of quantum-secured communication services. The
          QKD link replaces the channel that traditionally distributes
          symmetric keys for IPsec or similar tunnels between sites; the
          quantum guarantee is information-theoretic on the key delivery,
          while the data plane stays classical and uses the QKD-derived
          keys to encrypt traffic.<SourceNote id="bt-toshiba-press-2022" />
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="verified" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Verified claims</h2>
        <ul class="claim-list">
          <li><strong>Launched 26 April 2022 as the first commercial trial of a QKD-secured metro network in the UK.</strong><SourceNote id="bt-toshiba-press-2022" /></li>
          <li><strong>EY is the launch customer</strong>, connecting Canary Wharf and London Bridge offices.<SourceNote id="bt-toshiba-press-2022" /></li>
          <li><strong>Toshiba supplies the QKD hardware</strong>, developed at the Cambridge Quantum Technology Business Division.<SourceNote id="bt-toshiba-press-2022" /></li>
          <li><strong>Initial three-year operating term.</strong> Coverage of the launch consistently reports this as the planned commercial run; the network has continued to operate beyond the initial term.<SourceNote id="bt-toshiba-press-2022" /></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="caveats" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Things to note</h2>
        <ul class="caveat-list">
          <li><strong>Scope of the "world's first commercial QKD network" framing.</strong> Earlier commercial QKD services existed (e.g. Geneva 2007 election fibre, SwissQuantum); BT–Toshiba is the first commercial QKD trial offered by a tier-1 carrier in the UK as a productised managed service.</li>
          <li><strong>Prepare-and-measure, not entanglement-based.</strong> The QKD systems use Toshiba's prepare-and-measure protocols; the metro span is short enough that trusted relays are not part of the visible architecture.</li>
          <li><strong>Quantum-secured key distribution; classical data plane.</strong> Data traffic between EY's offices runs through classical encryption keyed by the QKD output, so the end-to-end security rests on classical key handling at the endpoints.</li>
          <li><strong>Paid trial, not a catalogue product.</strong> The service is a bilateral arrangement with EY plus selected follow-on customers; it is not a public BT product offered through the standard catalogue.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="related" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Related entries</h2>
        <ul class="related-list">
          <li><a href={url("/applications")}>Applications</a> — where commercial QKD sits in the application taxonomy.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/links")}>Links</a> — the metro-fibre regime QKD operates in.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/standards")}>Standards</a> — ETSI ISG-QKD and ITU-T Y.3800 series standards the service aligns with.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/case-studies/madqci")}>MadQCI</a> — multi-vendor research testbed contrast.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/case-studies/china-backbone")}>Beijing–Shanghai backbone</a> — single-vendor national QKD trunk contrast.</li>
          <li><a href={url("/companies/toshiba")}>Toshiba vendor dossier</a> — the QKD hardware supplier.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

<style>
  .hero { padding-block: var(--space-6) var(--space-4); border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-rule); display: grid; gap: var(--space-3); }
  .hero h1 { margin: 0; }
  .hero-meta { display: grid; gap: var(--space-1); margin: 0; padding: var(--space-3); background: var(--color-surface-2); border-radius: var(--radius); font-size: var(--text-sm); }
  .hero-meta div { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 11rem 1fr; gap: var(--space-2); }
  .hero-meta dt { color: var(--color-text-mute); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide); font-size: var(--text-xs); font-weight: 600; align-self: center; }
  .hero-meta dd { margin: 0; color: var(--color-text); }
  @media (max-width: 40rem) { .hero-meta div { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0; } }
  .claim-list, .caveat-list, .related-list { display: grid; gap: var(--space-2); padding-inline-start: var(--space-4); }
  .claim-list li, .caveat-list li { line-height: var(--leading-body); }
</style>
